ce:section.ce:para:
To further study the interaction between the Cr6P1 probe and Cr(VI) in H2SO4 (10 mM), a fluorescence titration experiment was investigated. With the addition of increasing concentrations of Cr(VI) to a solution of Cr6P1 (10 μM) in H2SO4 (10 mM), the emission at 502 nm decreased, it may duo to the quenching effect of the paramagnetic of Cr(VI) [32]. With the continuous increase of concentration of Cr(VI), there was accompanied by a continuous increase in the fluorescence intensity at 577 nm, which leading to the inhibition of the ESIPT process of the fluorescence probe Cr6P1 (Fig. 4
                        ). Most notably, a good linear relationship between the fluorescence intensity ratio (F577/F502) and the Cr(VI) concentration from 0 to 1 μM (Fig. 5
                        ) appeared. The detection limit (3σ/slope) of Cr6P1 for the determination of Cr(VI) was as low as 13 nM (6.9 × 10−4 mg/L), which is well meet the US EPA acceptable limit for Cr(VI) (0.1 mg/L, 1.9 μM) in drinking water [33,34].
